                        Ambassador in China (
                        Stuart
                    )</title></titleStmt><sourceDesc><bibl type="frus-volume-id">frus1947v07</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-id">d196</bibl><bibl type="frus-document-number">196</bibl><bibl type="frus-div-subtype">historical-document</bibl></sourceDesc></fileDesc><profileDesc><settingDesc><setting><date notBefore="1947-07-21T16:00:00-05:00" notAfter="1947-07-21T16:00:00-05:00"/></setting></settingDesc></profileDesc></teiHeader><text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-07-21T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-07-21T16:00:00-05:00" n="196" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d196">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/7–1747: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-07-21T17:00:00-04:00">July 21, 1947—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>897. I was glad that you had an opportunity to have such a talk as is reported in
                    your 1541 July 17. I share your views that conditions prevailing in China
                    require of the Generalissimo that he take effective measures to revitalize his
                    regime. To this end a first step would seem to be that he divest himself of
                    incompetent military and civil officials. However for the reasons implicit in my
                    821 July 3 noon I think it inappropriate for us make specific recommendations in
                    writing.</p>
                <p>I take it that you will show this correspondence to Gen. Wedemeyer whom I have of
                    course assured that he will be kept currently informed of matters having a
                    bearing on his mission.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
